04661nam a22007575i 9780231543262DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20162016nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802315432627 a10.7312/suba173462doi  a(DE-B1597)478161  a(OCoLC)979777072  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aBUS0450002bisacsh1 aSubacchi, Paola, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe People’s Money :bHow China Is Building a Global Currency /cPaola Subacchi. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (256 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- t1. Money is The Game Changer -- t2. China’s Extraordinary but Still Unfinished Transformation -- t3. A Financially Repressed Economy -- t4. China: A Trading Nation without an International Currency -- t5. Living with a Dwarf Currency -- t6. Creating an International Currency -- t7. Building a Market for The Renminbi -- t8. The Renminbi Moves Around -- t9. Managing is The Word -- t10. The Age of Chinese Money -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMany of the world's major economies boast dominant international currencies. Not so for China. Its renminbi has lagged far behind the pound, the euro, and the dollar in global circulation—and for good reason. China has long privileged economic policies that have fueled development at the expense of the renminbi's growth, and it has become clear that the underpowered currency is threatening China's future. The nation's leaders now face the daunting task of strengthening the currency without losing control of the nation's economy or risking total collapse. How are they approaching this challenge?In The People's Money, Paola Subacchi introduces readers to China's monetary system, mapping its evolution over the past century and, particularly, its transformation since Deng Xiaoping took power in 1978. Subacchi revisits the policies that fostered the country's economic rise while at the same time purposefully creating a currency of little use beyond China's borders. She shows the key to understanding China's economic predicament lies in past and future strategies for the renminbi. The financial turbulence following the global crisis of 2008, coupled with China's ambitions as a global creditor and chief economic power, has forced the nation to reckon with the limited international circulation of the renminbi. Increasing the currency's reach will play a major role in securing China's future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aFinancezChina. 0aForeign exchangezChina. 0aMonetary policyzChina. 0aRenminbi. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Money & Monetary Policy.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311063857808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2016z9783110485103oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Economics 2016z9783110485158oZDB-23-DBV40uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/suba1734640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231543262423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231543262.jpg  a978-3-11-063857-8  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-DBVb2016  aZDB-23-DGGb2016